{
  "doc_id": "44014",
  "text": "Selenium was found to be implied in many diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, lung cancer,adultT-cell leukemia [CITATION_1] . Indeed a lower selenium level was found in patient with all described illnesses compared to healthy subjects [CITATION_2] . Some authors reported that Selenium concentration in blood decreases according to the magnitude of the inflammatory response [CITATION_3] . Similarly, other authors finding revealed that supplementation with selenium had an immune-stimulant effects including an improvement of proliferation of activated T cells [CITATION_4] . As regards TBI patients, our data may suggest that selenium may not play a role in death of patients with TBI. Selenium levels were not higher in patients who died from a TBI compared to patients who survived after TBI. Moreover, the difference of selenium level in patients with TBI and healthy subjects was not significant. Otherwise, Selenium was also studied with C-reactive protein in many illnesses and the results demonstrated an important role of C-reactive protein in the acute phase response in several ones such as rheumatoid arthritis, lung cancer, adult T-cell leukemia [CITATION_5] . In fact, the level of CRP was higher in patients with different diseases compared to healthy subjects [CITATION_6] . The C-reactive protein was widely reported as a marker for underlying systemic inflammation [CITATION_7] . Furthermore, a strong correlation between serum CRP level and severity of brain injury in patients was also reported [CITATION_8] . Besides, selenium and CRP Page number not for citation purposes 4 serum levels were found to be related to age and gender in healthy subjects [CITATION_9] . In contrast, our data did not show any significance of selenium concentration (D0, D2 and D4) in patients according to gender. Selenium concentration in the human body was found to vary with age [CITATION_10] . For instance, selenium concentration in fetal brain decreased with age, but increased with age post natally [19] .",
